Now, imagine the scenario if those same creators were invested in the game they were playing?

Now, the creator doesn't need to focus as much time and energy on getting donations, selling merchandise, or catering their content to family-friendly advertising.

7/14

Gaming creators make content for a game they enjoy playing and monetize through ads, merch, brand deals, and donations.

But, the video game company gets free marketing and 100% of the upside.

6/14

Gaming companies give you a free license to create content, and you can monetize that content to make a living.

If you're a larger creator, you may even get a brand deal from the company to promote their game or a free game code.

Sounds great, right?

5/14

The video game industry was one of the first major industries to adapt to creators, and many games have focused entirely on creator marketing to promote their games.

For many creators, the current system feels fair.

4/14

Making a living as a gaming content creator is incredibly difficult. 

For every creator that makes a full-time living, there are thousands of others grinding away for their chance in the spotlight.

3/14

I was part of the first wave of creators that made a living creating video game content on YouTube and Twitch in 2009.

Since 2009, most of the gaming industry has been controlled by YouTubers and Twitch creators. 

What they play becomes popular and part of pop culture.
2/14
